Example \(\PageIndex{3}\) If \(\sin (	heta )=\dfrac{3}{7}\) and \(	heta\) is in the second quadrant, find \(\cos (	heta )\). Solution Substituting the known value for sine into the Pythagorean identity, \[\cos ^{2} (	heta )+\sin ^{2} (	heta )=1
onumber\] \[\cos ^{2} (	heta )+\dfrac{9}{49} =1
onumber\] \[\cos ^{2} (	heta )=\dfrac{40}{49}
onumber\] \[\cos (	heta )=\pm \sqrt{\dfrac{40}{49} } =\pm \dfrac{\sqrt{40} }{7} =\pm \dfrac{2\sqrt{10} }{7}
onumber\] Since the angle is in the second quadrant, we know the \(x\) value of the point would be negative, so the cosine value should also be negative. Using this additional information, we can conclude that \[\cos (	heta )=-\dfrac{2\sqrt{10} }{7}
onumber\]
